  description="The hardest essay we will publish. The assumption that adult children will provide elder care is, mathematically, false for most middle-class households. Here is what to do instead."
>
  <p>There is a sentence I have watched parents say out loud, with complete sincerity, hundreds of times.</p>

  <p><em>"If anything goes wrong, the kids will help."</em></p>

  <p>It is said at kitchen tables when retirement is discussed. It is said in financial advisor offices when the long-term care question comes up. It is said in hospital waiting rooms when the conversation turns toward what happens next. It is said with the certainty of a parent who has spent thirty years being needed, loved, and counted on by their children, and who cannot quite believe that the relationship runs only one direction now.</p>

  <p>It is also, in the vast majority of cases, wrong.</p>

  <p>Not because the children are bad. Not because the love is gone. But because the math of modern adult life does not contain enough hours, enough money, or enough proximity for the parent care that previous generations took for granted. And because the parent saying the sentence has rarely tested it against any of the data that would tell them whether it is true for their specific situation.</p>

  <p>This is the hardest essay I will write on this site, because it is the one that asks you to give up a belief that has been comforting you, quietly, for years. The belief that you have raised something that will, when the moment comes, raise you back.</p>

  <p>You have not. Almost nobody has. And the planning you do in the next three years — while you are still strong enough to do it — depends entirely on whether you can look that fact in the face.</p>

  <h2>The lie has a name</h2>

  <p>Sociologists call it <em>filial piety expectation</em> — the cross-generational assumption that adult children will provide material care to aging parents. It is one of the oldest social contracts in human history. For most of the last 10,000 years, it was also one of the most reliable.</p>

  <p>It is not reliable anymore.</p>

  <p>In 2024, only 12% of Americans aged 65 or older lived with an adult child. The figure has been falling steadily since the 1940s. The corresponding figure in 1900 was 57%. We are watching, in slow motion, the unwinding of a multi-generational living arrangement that defined what aging looked like for almost everyone who came before us.</p>

  <p>The reasons are not mysterious:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Adult children move for jobs. The average American moves 11 times in a lifetime. The probability that your adult child lives within 30 miles of you at the moment you need them is now about 40%, and it falls every year.</li>
    <li>Adult children work longer hours. The average American works 1,791 hours per year, the highest in the developed world. They do not have spare capacity for parent care.</li>
    <li>Adult children have their own children later. The average age of first-time motherhood in the US is now 27.3 and climbing. By the time you need care, your adult child may be in the deepest part of their own parenting years — preschool drop-offs, elementary school, sports, college applications — with no margin for you.</li>
    <li>Adult children divorce, get sick, lose jobs, struggle with mental health, develop addictions. Roughly 25% of adult Americans report a serious mental health condition. The adult child you are counting on may, statistically, be in worse shape than you are.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>And then there is the simplest and least-discussed reason: many adult children, when asked privately and honestly, do not consider it their responsibility to provide hands-on care to their parents. They love you. They want you to be well. They do not see themselves as your future caregiver, and many of them — politely, quietly — have been clear about this for years, in ways you may not have wanted to hear.</p>

  <p>This is not a moral failing on their part. It is the predictable result of how the economy, the culture, and the geography of modern adult life now work.</p>

  <p>You can call it sad. You cannot call it wrong. And you cannot plan around it.</p>

  <h2>What "the kids will help" actually means in practice</h2>

  <p>Let me describe what <em>the kids will help</em> looks like when it actually happens. I have watched this scenario play out at close range in maybe two dozen families now, including my own extended family. The pattern is remarkably consistent.</p>

  <p>A parent in their late 70s or early 80s has a medical event. A fall. A small stroke. A cancer diagnosis. The first hospitalization. The adult children — there are usually two or three of them, scattered across one or two time zones — fly in or drive in. There is an emergency week. Hospital visits. Conversations with doctors. Logistics. Casseroles. The parent is moved home or to a rehab facility.</p>

  <p>For the next three to eight weeks, one adult child takes the lead. Almost always a daughter. She uses her vacation days. She uses sick leave. She works remotely when she can. She organizes the medical appointments, talks to the insurance company, fights with the pharmacy, fills the pillbox, drives to follow-ups. Her marriage strains. Her children miss her. Her boss begins, very gently, to ask when she will be back full-time.</p>

  <p>At week six or eight, paid help is brought in. A home health aide three days a week. Then five. Within six months, the situation is almost entirely managed by professional caregivers, paid out of the parent's savings, with the adult children dropping in for major decisions and weekends.</p>

  <p>This is the <em>successful</em> version. This is what <em>the kids will help</em> actually looks like when it works. Six to eight weeks of intense daughter-driven care, followed by a transition to paid care that the parent funds themselves.</p>

  <p>The unsuccessful versions:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>No daughter, only sons. Care arrives slower and thinner.</li>
    <li>The lead child has young children of their own and can give two weeks, not eight.</li>
    <li>The lead child lives across the country and can only manage logistics by phone.</li>
    <li>There is estrangement, or one sibling who refuses to participate, and the conflict consumes more energy than the care.</li>
    <li>The parent has been emotionally difficult for years and the children show up out of obligation, not warmth, and leave the moment paid help is available.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>In none of these cases — the successful one or the unsuccessful ones — do the adult children become the long-term solution. They become the emergency response team. The emergency lasts somewhere between three weeks and three months. After that, the problem is yours, and it is solved with money, paid professionals, or institutional care.</p>

  <p>If you do not have the money, you do not have the option.</p>

  <h2>The numbers that should keep you awake</h2>

  <p>Here is what the United States Department of Health and Human Services projects for someone turning 65 in 2026:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>70% chance of needing some form of long-term care at some point</li>
    <li>Average duration of needed care: 3 years</li>
    <li>Average duration for women: 3.7 years; for men: 2.2 years</li>
    <li>20% will need care for more than 5 years</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Here is what that care costs, in 2026 dollars:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Home health aide, 44 hours per week: $75,500 per year</li>
    <li>Adult day care: $24,700 per year</li>
    <li>Assisted living facility: $64,200 per year</li>
    <li>Nursing home, semi-private room: $108,400 per year</li>
    <li>Nursing home, private room: $123,500 per year</li>
    <li>Memory care unit: $86,400 to $140,000 per year</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Three years of nursing home care in a private room: roughly $370,500.</p>

  <p>Five years: roughly $617,500.</p>

  <p>Seven years (the high-end case, which 1 in 10 people experience): approximately $864,500.</p>

  <p>Medicare does not cover any of this for stays longer than 100 days. Medicaid covers it only after you have spent down nearly all of your assets — generally to less than $2,000 in countable assets in most states. The house may be protected during a spouse's lifetime; almost nothing else is.</p>

  <p>The plan that says <em>the kids will help</em> is, mathematically, the plan that says: <em>my children will personally absorb a six-figure cost or provide a five-figure-per-year time commitment for an indefinite period while continuing their own jobs and parenting their own children.</em></p>

  <p>When you write the sentence out that way, you can see why almost no adult child can do it.</p>

  <h2>"But my daughter is different"</h2>

  <p>This is the sentence that comes next. <em>My daughter is different. She has told me she will take care of us.</em></p>

  <p>I believe you. I believe she means it. I have heard versions of this from parents whose daughters are wonderful, devoted, capable people.</p>

  <p>Here is what I have also seen, repeatedly:</p>

  <p>The daughter who promised her mother that she would never put her in a nursing home discovers, at the moment of decision, that home care is going to cost $80,000 a year. She does not have $80,000 a year. Her mother does not have $80,000 a year. The nursing home, paid for by Medicaid after the spend-down, is the only available option. The promise was real. The arithmetic is also real. The arithmetic wins.</p>

  <p>The daughter who said she would move her father in with her family discovers, six months in, that her father has dementia that wakes him at 3 a.m. confused and frightened, and that her marriage is in crisis, and that her children are not okay, and that she cannot do this for the next four to six years, which is the most likely remaining duration. The father goes to assisted living. The daughter spends ten years feeling guilty.</p>

  <p>The daughter who took six months of unpaid leave to care for her mother loses her health insurance, depletes her own retirement savings to cover expenses, and re-enters the workforce two years later at a position one rung below where she was. Her mother lives another six years. The daughter's own retirement is now meaningfully worse off because of the choice she made.</p>

  <p>These are not failures of love. They are the predictable consequences of asking a working-age adult to absorb the financial and time costs of an aging parent in a country whose social systems do not support that arrangement. The daughters who keep their promises pay for them with their own retirements, their own marriages, and their own children's wellbeing. The daughters who break their promises live with the guilt.</p>

  <p>The kindest thing you can do for your daughter, right now, while you are still healthy, is to build the financial structure that does not require her to choose between her life and yours.</p>

  <h2>What you actually need to plan, in dollars</h2>

  <p>Here is the math you should run this month. Not next year. This month.</p>

  <p><strong>The 70% scenario:</strong> Assume a 70% probability you will need at least three years of paid care, averaging $75,000 per year. That is a $225,000 cost, in addition to all your other retirement expenses. If you and your spouse both need care — which happens often, sometimes simultaneously — double that.</p>

  <p><strong>The 20% scenario:</strong> Assume a 20% probability you will need more than five years of care. At an average of $80,000 per year over five years, that is $400,000. Above $400,000 for the long tail.</p>

  <p><strong>The combined household scenario:</strong> A married couple, ages 62 and 65 in 2026, with $850,000 in retirement assets, is currently overestimating their financial safety. If both of them live to average life expectancy and both require average care, the combined cost of their last decade can range from $400,000 to $1.1 million, depending on geography, choices, and timing. That is on top of normal retirement spending of $50,000 to $80,000 per year.</p>

  <p>The math does not work for most middle-class households. It is not supposed to. The American long-term care system was not designed to work for the middle class. It was designed to work for the wealthy (who self-fund) and the poor (who qualify for Medicaid). Everyone in between — which is most parents reading this — falls into a gap that has no good solution unless you plan for it deliberately, in advance.</p>

  <blockquote>
    <strong>The hard truth</strong>
    If your retirement plan assumes your adult children will absorb long-term care costs in money or in time, your retirement plan is not a plan. It is a hope. The difference matters when you are 79 and the bill arrives.
  </blockquote>

  <h2>The four real options</h2>

  <p>If your adult children are not your plan, what is?</p>

  <p>There are exactly four real strategies. Most parents will choose some combination. None of them is comfortable. All of them are better than the hoping strategy.</p>

  <h3>1. Self-fund through deliberate over-saving</h3>

  <p>This is the wealthy person's strategy and a stretch goal for the upper middle class. It requires a dedicated long-term care fund of $400,000 to $700,000, separate from ordinary retirement savings, mentally walled off as "for the bad scenario." Most middle-class parents cannot get there. Some can, if they extend their working years by three to five and save aggressively in the last decade of work.</p>

  <p>The advantage of self-funding is total control: you choose where you go, who provides care, and when. The disadvantage is that the money is locked into a worst-case scenario it may never need to fund, money that could otherwise be spent or given away. Bill Perkins' <em>Die With Zero</em> makes the case that this is a worse outcome than people realize; many parents over-save and die with hundreds of thousands they never enjoyed.</p>

  <h3>2. Long-term care insurance (traditional or hybrid)</h3>

  <p>Traditional long-term care insurance has gotten worse over the past two decades. Premiums have risen sharply. Carriers have left the market. Policies have been canceled or restructured downward. Buying a new traditional LTC policy at age 60 today is expensive — typically $3,000 to $7,000 per year per person — and the policy may have lifetime caps that cover only 40% of the realistic cost.</p>

  <p>Hybrid life insurance / long-term care policies are now more common. You buy a permanent life insurance policy with an LTC rider. If you need care, you draw from the policy. If you don't, your heirs get the death benefit. The premiums are higher upfront but the money does not "disappear" if you stay healthy. For many parents in their late 50s and early 60s, this is the most practical structure available.</p>

  <p>The realistic LTC insurance plan covers somewhere between 30% and 70% of a serious care event, depending on policy design. It is a partial solution, not a complete one. But partial is dramatically better than nothing.</p>

  <h3>3. Medicaid planning (legal asset restructuring)</h3>

  <p>This is the option most middle-class parents do not know exists and should learn about by age 60 at the latest.</p>

  <p>Medicaid will pay for nursing home care if you have spent down nearly all your assets. The mistake most people make is that they assume the spend-down has to be a literal liquidation of everything they own. That is not how the law works.</p>

  <p>There are legal strategies — irrevocable Medicaid asset protection trusts, life estates, certain annuity structures, and others — that allow you to legally transfer assets out of your countable estate while you are still healthy, so that if you need long-term care, you qualify for Medicaid without having to lose the house and the savings to the state.</p>

  <p>The catch is the <strong>five-year lookback rule</strong>: most asset transfers must happen at least five years before you apply for Medicaid. This means the Medicaid-planning conversation has to happen when you are healthy and 60 to 67 years old, not when you are 78 and already declining.</p>

  <p>A good elder-law attorney charges $4,000 to $10,000 for a comprehensive Medicaid plan. For most middle-class parents with $300,000 to $1.5 million in net worth, this is the single highest-ROI legal expense available, and it is also the one almost nobody undertakes until it is too late.</p>

  <h3>4. Move to a structure that has care built in</h3>

  <p>A CCRC (continuing care retirement community) sells you a single solution: independent living now, assisted living when you need it, skilled nursing when you need that. You pay a large entry fee (typically $300,000 to $1 million, refundable in some structures) plus a monthly fee ($3,000 to $7,000 per month) for the rest of your life.</p>

  <p>It is expensive. It is also, for the right person, the most rational answer available, because it eliminates the need to make a panicked move at 82 from a position of weakness. The decision is made once, in your late 60s or early 70s, while you are still in charge of your own choices.</p>

  <p>International alternatives — moving to Portugal, Costa Rica, Mexico, or Thailand for the lower cost of long-term care — are increasingly being chosen by parents who do the math and decide that aging in the US is unaffordable. This is a real option. It is also a one-way decision that separates you from grandchildren, friends, and existing medical care. Most parents who consider it do not do it. Some should.</p>

  <blockquote>
    <strong>The hard math</strong>
    A combination strategy — partial LTC insurance covering 40%, Medicaid asset protection covering 30%, dedicated savings covering 30% — is the realistic plan for most middle-class households. The plan that covers 100% with no insurance, no legal restructuring, and no dedicated savings does not exist. Stop pretending it does.
  </blockquote>

  <h2>What to actually do this quarter</h2>

  <p>If you are between 55 and 70 and you have not had this conversation with anyone other than yourself, here is the order of operations.</p>

  <p><strong>Month 1: Run the numbers.</strong> Sit down with your spouse if you are married. Add up: liquid retirement savings, home equity, expected Social Security, expected pensions, planned working years remaining. Subtract: expected ordinary retirement spending over 30 years, expected one-time costs (final home, car replacements, weddings, helping the kids with down payments — set a cap on this last one). What you have left is your long-term care budget. Compare it to the $225,000 to $700,000 range above. You will likely have a gap. Quantify it.</p>

  <p><strong>Month 2: Get the professional input.</strong> Schedule three meetings:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>A fee-only fiduciary financial planner ($2,500 to $5,000 for a comprehensive plan)</li>
    <li>An elder-law attorney specializing in Medicaid planning ($300 to $500 for an initial consultation, $4,000 to $10,000 for a full plan if you proceed)</li>
    <li>An insurance broker who specializes in hybrid LTC insurance (free consultations are standard; commissions come from the carrier)</li>
  </ul>
  <p>You do not have to use all three. You have to know what each of them sees in your situation.</p>

  <p><strong>Month 3: Have the conversation with your adult children.</strong> Not the <em>promise me you'll take care of me</em> conversation. The <em>here is what I am doing so that you do not have to</em> conversation. Tell them you are building a long-term care plan. Tell them what it is. Tell them what you do and do not expect from them, in plain words. Most adult children, hearing this conversation for the first time, feel an enormous wave of relief. The conversation about parent care is the conversation neither generation knows how to start. Start it yourself, from a position of strength, while you are still strong. It will be one of the most important conversations of your life.</p>

  <h2>The deepest reason to do this</h2>

  <p>Here is the part of this essay I have been hesitating to write.</p>

  <p>The reason to plan for long-term care without relying on your children is not, in the end, about money. It is about something subtler and harder.</p>

  <p>If you do not plan, your children will be put into an impossible position at the moment of your decline. They will have to choose between their lives and yours. Most of them will choose their lives, slowly, with guilt, in a series of small decisions that they will not entirely admit to themselves. Some will choose yours, and pay for it for the rest of their own lives.</p>

  <p>Either way, the relationship that you spent thirty years building — the relationship of parent and adult child, the one you wanted to be characterized by love, respect, and mutual independence — gets warped by the unspoken expectation. Every visit becomes a negotiation about the future. Every decision about your health becomes a decision about their freedom. Every conversation gets the weight of <em>what happens when she really needs us</em> sitting underneath it.</p>

  <p>The parent who has planned, who has the money or the insurance or the Medicaid structure or the CCRC waiting, gives their children a different kind of gift. They give them the freedom to love them without owing them care. They give them visits that are visits, not assessments. They give them a relationship that is allowed to remain a relationship, instead of slowly becoming a logistics problem.</p>

  <p>This is the deepest reason to plan. Not to spare yourself the indignity of dependence — though that matters too. Not to preserve your money — though that matters too. The reason to plan is to spare your children the role of caretaker that none of you signed up for, and to preserve the relationship you actually want to have with them in the last fifteen years of your life.</p>

  <p>You raised them so that they could leave.</p>

  <p>The final gift of a well-raised adult is to never have to come back as the rescuer.</p>

  <p>You are still strong enough, today, to give them that gift. Most parents wait until they cannot, and then the gift becomes a burden, and the burden becomes the relationship.</p>

  <p>Do not be most parents.</p>

  <p>Run the numbers. Make the calls. Build the structure. Have the conversation.</p>

  <p>You raised them. Now build the parent they will never have to rescue.</p>

  <p>— <em>M. Holloway</em></p>

